\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\sl259\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid5911984 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5911984 <hi rend="bold">Further Particulars of the California Crusoe.</hi>
\par 
\par Some time ago there appeared in the <emph>Bulletin</emph> a
n interesting narrative, written by Capt. C. J. W. Russell, of an eighteen years' residence alone, by a Californian Indian woman, upon the island of San Nicolas, one of the Santa Barbara group. This narrative had drawn forth some relative remarks by the L
o
s Angeles <emph>Star</emph> and the Santa Barbara <emph>Gazette</emph>. It would seem, from their accounts, that Capt. Russell has <emph>colored</emph> his narrative somewhat; or, at leas, that his description of the story is not the one generally receive
d in the lower country. {\*\atrfstart 398026103}
As the whole circumstances are very curious, and may form the foundation of some romance by a future Defore (like the tale of Alexander Selkirk, the castaway on Juan Fernandez, which swelled into "Robinson Crusoe" of the novelist), w
ho take occasion to lay some additional particulars of the original narrative before our readers.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid9450872 {\*\atrfend 398026103}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn 
{\*\annotation{\*\atnref 398026103}{\*\atndate -953705513}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid9450872 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9450872 Girl Crusoe}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5911984 
\par 
\par The Los Angeles <emph>Star</emph> is indebted to Mr. J. J. Warner&#8212;"than whom no man is better acquainted with modern transactions of this coast"&#8212;for the following facts on this subject:
\par 
\par Most of these islands forming the group to the south of Point Concepcion, were, at the time of the subjugation of Upper California by the Cross and Spanish arms, inhabited by 
the Indians of the same race as those along the main. In the earlier period of the Missions, which were established within the present limits of this State, the inhabitants of those islands nearest the coast were brought over and incorporated with the neo
p
hites of Santa Barbara, San Buenaventura and San Gabriel. The island of San Nicolas, being much farther seaward, the natives holding no intercourse with those of the main land, and but little, if any, with those of the islands adjacent to the coast, were 
undisturbed.
\par 
\par {\*\atrfstart 398026104}
In the prosecution of the business of collecting furs along the coast by the Russian Fur Company, a large party of traders and hunters, composed of Russians, half-breeds and Kodiac Indians, were, in 1818, hunting and trading at the island of S
an Nicolas. During their stay at the island, jealousies sprung up, and with them difficulties and broils occurred between the hunters and natives.{\*\atrfstart 398026261}
 The inhabitants were simple and harmless, their numbers insufficient to cause internal discord, and their remote situation offered no opportunity to cultivate the science of war. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid263772 
{\*\atrfend 398026261}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 398026261}{\*\atndate 1193888490}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid263772 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid263772 Noble savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5911984 The hunters and traders were the reverse of harmlessness and simplicity, and without difficulty or loss on their part, exterminated all of the inhabitants which they could discover, exce
pt a small number of the females, whom they carried away with them on their departure.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5515365 {\*\atrfend 398026104}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 398026104}
{\*\atndate -953705512}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5515365 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5515365 Anti-Russian sentiment; Indians as savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5911984 
 Two men and two women were undiscovered in their hiding place, and after the sailing of the hunting party, remained the only inhabitants of the island. {\*\atrfstart 398026105}
Their numbers were increased by the slow but gradual course of nature until 1836, when the population consisted of seven persons, four males and three females, one of whom, of about twenty years ofyears, was of a fairer tint than her companions}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid83818 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid83818 {\*\atrfend 398026105}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 398026105}{\*\atndate -1490490019}\ltrpar 
\pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid83818 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid83818 Noble Savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5911984 
\par The otter hunters, from Santa Barbara and Los Angeles, who, from 1830 to 1836, in the prosecution of their business along the shore of the main land and the neighboring Islands, sometimes extended the scene of their operations to the more remote Island. 
{\*\atrfstart 398026106}The reports which they give of the timid half-breed maiden of San Nicolas occasioned considerable sensation among their fellow-hunters who had not visited the Island, or who, 
on their visits, had not been so fortunate as to discover the inhabitants, who invariably sought to avoid the observation of strangers.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5515365 {\*\atrfend 398026106}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor 
Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 398026106}{\*\atndate -953705510}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5515365 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5515365 Noble savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5911984 
 Repeated attempts were made by the hunters, at various times, to induce this sol
itary family to hold intercourse with them, but which were only partially successful. In the summer of 1836, an American and an Englishman, residents of Los Angeles, sent an expedition from San Pedro to San Nicolas for the purpose of bringing away this fa
mily. After much delay and difficulty in accomplishing this object, they succeeded in getting six of the seven persons on board of their vessel, and sailed for San Pedro. {\*\atrfstart 398026107}
They were brought to Los Angeles, where, from the change of diet and habit, they soon sickened and died, with the exception of one old man and one middle-aged female. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5515365 {\*\atrfend 398026107}
